Tessie\ncar_status=$(tessie parse car status 2>&1)\n\n# Get local Nashville news using RSS feeds\nlocal_news=$(curl -s \"https://www.wsch.com/feed/news.rss\" | grep -E title>|<item>|<desc\" | head -n 3 | tr -d '\\n' | sed 's/<[^>]*>//g')\n\n# Get Google Routes traffic info\ntraffic_info=$(curl -s \"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/distancematrix/json?origins=36.1658,-86.7878&destinations=36.1462,-86.7855&key=SEMO_KEY&units=imperial\" | jq '.rows[0].elements[0].duration.text')\n\n# Format output\nif [ \"$car_status\" == \"success\" ]; then\n    car_status=\"Online\"\nelse\n    car_status=\"Offline - $car_status\"\nfi\n\necho \"=== 6:30 AM Nashville Brief ===\"\necho \"🚗 Car Status: $car_status\"\necho \"🗞️ Local News Highlights:\"\necho \"$local_news\"\necho \"🚦 Traffic Conditions (Downtown): $traffic_info minutes\"\necho\n\necho \"=== 4:00 PM Nashville Brief ===\"\necho \"🚗 Car Status: $car_status\"\necho \"🗞️ Local News Highlight:\"\necho \"$local_news\" | tail -n 1\necho \"🚦 Traffic Conditions (City): $traffic_info minutes\"\n\nThis looks correct. The script seems well-formed. So why is there an error when running the cron job?\n\nThe error is not in the script itself, but in the cron job's command. The cron job is trying to execute the script, but the error is about an unexpected EOF in a string. That suggests that the command being executed (the script) has a syntax error in its command line. But the cron job's command is simply the path to the script. Unless the script's path is incorrect, this shouldn't be the case.\n\nWait, maybe the script is correct, but when the cron job runs it, there's an issue with environment variables or something else. Alternatively, maybe the script is correct, but there's an error in how it's being called. However, the error message points to the cron job's command line, not the script.\n\nAlternatively, maybe the script is correct, but when the cron job runs it, there's an issue with the environment. For example, maybe the tessie or curl commands are not installed, or there's a missing API key. But the error message doesn't indicate that.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps the script is correct, but when the cron job tries to run it, there's a problem with the path. For example, if the path is incorrect. But the user already confirmed the path is correct.\n\nThis is getting complicated. The error is happening when the cron job tries to execute the script. The error is about an unexpected EOF in a string. That would happen if, in the script, there's a string that starts with a quote but doesn't close it. For example:\n\necho \"Hello world\"\n\nBut if the script has:\n\necho \"Hello\" world\"\n\nThat would cause an error because the second quote is not closed. The shell expects a closing quote after \"Hello\".\n\nLooking at the script provided earlier, let's check for such issues. The script has:\n\nlocal_news=$(curl -s \"https://www.wsch.com/feed/news.rss\" | grep -E title>|<item>|<desc\" | head -n 3 | tr -d '\\n' | sed 's/<[^>]*>//g')\n\nHere, the grep command uses | <item> and | <desc\". If those are not properly escaped, that could cause issues. For example, if the quotes around title, item, or desc are not escaped, the shell would interpret them as variables or patterns, leading to syntax errors.\n\nIn the script provided, the grep command is:\n\ngrep -E title>|<item>|<desc\" | head -n 3 | tr -d '\\n' | sed 's/<[^>]*>//g'\n\nBut the title> is not escaped. In a here-string or in command substitution, if you don't escape >, it would be interpreted as redirection. This would cause a syntax error because the shell expects > to be a redirection operator, but it's inside a string.\n\nAh, here's the problem! The grep command in the script is:\n\ngrep -E title>|<item>|<desc\" | head -n 3 | tr -d '\\n' | sed 's/<[^>]*>//g'\n\nThe > after title is not escaped. In the context of the script, this is inside a here-string or command substitution. If the script is using command substitution (like $(...)), then the > would be treated as redirection, which is invalid in that context. This would cause a syntax error.\n\nSimilarly, the <item> and <desc\" are not escaped. In a here-string, if you don't escape < or >, they are treated as part of the string. However, in the grep command, <item> and <desc\" are part of the pattern. If they are not escaped, the shell would interpret them as filename globbing patterns, which is not intended.\n\nFor example, if the RSS feed has an item with a title containing \"item\", the grep would match it, but that's not the intention. The intention was to match the exact tags <item> and <desc\". By not escaping the < and >, the grep would treat them as pattern anchors, leading to incorrect matches.\n\nThis is a critical error in the script. The same applies to the <desc\" part. The \" at the end is not escaped, so in the here-string, it would close the string early, causing the pattern to be incomplete.\n\nSo, the script has multiple syntax errors in the grep and sed commands due to unescaped special characters. This would cause the script to fail when trying to fetch the local news and process the traffic info.\n\nTo fix this, all instances of <, >, |, and \" in the grep and sed commands need to be properly escaped. For example:\n\nIn the grep command:\n\ngrep -E \"title>|<item>|<desc\\\"\" \n\nIn the sed command:\n\ns'<[^>]*'//g'\n\nAlso, ensure that all quotes are properly closed and that any special characters are escaped where necessary.\n\nAnother issue is in the sed command:\n\nsed 's/<[^>]*>//g'\n\nThe < and > are not escaped. In sed, this would be interpreted as a range from < to >, which is not intended. They should be escaped as < and >.\n\nAdditionally, the traffic_info command uses:\n\ncurl -s \"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/distancematrix/json?origins=36.1658,-86.7878&destinations=36.1462,-86.7855&key=SEMO_KEY&units=imperial\" | jq '.rows[0].elements[0].duration.text'\n\nHere, the single quotes around the URL are correct, but if the URL contains characters that need escaping, that could be an issue. However, in this case, the URL seems correct.\n\nSo, to fix the script:\n\n1. Escape all >, <, |, and \" in the grep and sed commands.\n2. Ensure that all quotes are properly closed.\n3. Escape any other special characters that might cause issues in command substitution.\n\nOnce these are fixed, the script should correctly fetch the local news and traffic info.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"jyqYKvxHG","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"chmod +x /home/ec2-user/.openclaw/workspace/tools/nashville_brief.sh"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/free","usage":{"input":57062,"output":7229,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":64291,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772456660953}}
