{"type":"message","id":"947d31ef","parentId":"50ab60ad","timestamp":"2026-03-02T16:08:59.116Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let me try to figure out what's going on here. The user is trying to get the nesting-conversations skill working, specifically for the Nashville morning briefs. They've gone through several steps, including installing various tools, checking cron jobs, and troubleshooting issues with missing commands. The last few steps involved trying to install the Tessie skill using OpenClaw, but there was an error saying \"unknown command 'install'\". \n\nWait, the user mentioned that the Tessie skill is listed in skills.md. So maybe instead of using OpenClaw's install command, they need to manually set it up. The user tried \"clawhub install tessie\" and got a response saying it's already installed. That suggests that the skill is present but not functioning correctly.\n\nThe user's script for the Nashville brief uses \"tessie parse car status\", but the system is throwing an error that tessie isn't a command. The previous assistant tried installing via OpenClaw, which didn't work, then suggested clawhub install, which said it's already installed. So maybe the skill is installed but not properly configured in the environment.\n\nLooking at the skills.md file, the Tessie skill might be there, but the OpenClaw environment might not have it in the PATH. The user's system calls \"which tessie\" don't find it, so even if the skill is installed, the CLI isn't accessible. The solution would involve either reinstalling with --force, manually setting the PATH, or ensuring the correct version is used.\n\nAlternatively, maybe the Tessie CLI isn't compatible with the current environment, and the user needs to use a different method to parse car status, like using OpenClaw's built-in tools instead of the Tessie CLI. The user's main goal is to get car status (battery, location), so if Tessie isn't working, perhaps there's